      "start_time": 16,
      "end_time": 22,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "This sample comes from episode "
            },
            {
              "text": "Upstage",
              "link": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-35t77mpd"
            },
            {
              "text": ". In this program "
            },
            {
              "text": "Say Brother ",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": "shines the spotlight on the New England arts scene and asks why local artists and performers feel forced to move to places like New York and Los Angeles in order to find steady work. Guests include Evelyn Moore, actress and coauthor of the Emmy Award-winning \"Black Dyad,\" and John Ross and Victoria Howard, Music Director and and Producer, respectively, of the Boston hit play \"Dancin' in the Street.\""
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "tags": [],
      "uuid": "ba3348c4-bbaa-46ff-a9cc-13a177f929e6"
    },
    {
      "start_time": 0,
      "end_time": 3,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "The American Archive of Public Broadcasting",
              "link": "https://americanarchive.org/"
            },
            {
              "text": " (AAPB) is a collaboration between the Library of Congress and GBH that seeks to preserve and make accessible significant historical content created by public media stations, and to coordinate a national effort to save at-risk public media before its content is lost to posterity. The American Archive of Public Broadcasting contains more than 250,000 digitized public broadcasting programs and original materials. Some notable programs are featured curated Special Collections. Each Special Collection finding aid provides detailed information about the content, such as its creator, recommended search strategies, and related resources. The \"Say Brother/Basic Black\" collection launched in June 2025, offers public access to just under a thousand episodes, episode segments, and interviews from GBH’s longest-running public affairs television program produced by, for, and about the Black community. \n"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "tags": [],
      "uuid": "853fda26-e76f-41fa-acae-5eb8d1a3c5f6"
    },
    {
      "start_time": 4,
      "end_time": 9,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Say Brother",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " (1968-1997) premiered three months after the assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr. and gave voice to Black perspectives during a period of racial protest and rapid social change. In 1998, "
            },
            {
              "text": "Say Brother",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " became "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://www.wgbh.org/basic-black",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Basic Black",
                  "italic": true
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " (1998-2024), a title that producer Cynthia Johnson felt was more inclusive of women."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "From the outset, "
            },
            {
              "text": "Say Brother",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " served as a forum for activists to critique the racial status quo and for Black writers, musicians, and artists to showcase Black culture. "
            },
            {
              "text": "Say Brother",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " tackled local and international issues of vital interest to Black Bostonians, including the "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-587780d5535",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Black Power Movement"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-6h4cn6z40j",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "liberation struggles in Africa"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", the "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-9nc5sc3d",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Equal Rights Amendment"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", the rising "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-708wbmr9",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "cost of housing"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " in the Boston area, and the legacy of the "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-171vjgmx",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Vietnam War"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ". Episodes also addressed topics in world history and culture, such as the "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-5cd6cb793f8",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "ethnic history of Puerto Rico"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-0ed8683064b",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "racial stereotyping in the 19th century"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-f6ae4901d78",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Africa’s contribution"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " to ancient Greek, Roman, Chinese, and Middle Eastern civilizations."
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "tags": [],
      "uuid": "29ff8bd8-1abf-4394-9ae1-d840c293d684"
    },
