    {
      "start_time": 36,
      "end_time": 40,
      "annotation": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "text": "Basic Black",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " continued the work that "
            },
            {
              "text": "Say Brother",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " began, covering issues affecting people of color in Greater Boston and beyond. Episodes tackled social injustices, such as "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-83kwhw47",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "racial profiling"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-40xpqhsc",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "discriminatory lending"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-71nggqf3",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "medical racism"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ". Other episodes celebrated the positive impact of "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-61djk9v6",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "local community organizations"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ", and in a "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-558d10hh",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "roundtable discussion"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " following the 2008 presidential election, panelists voiced cautious optimism about the significance of Barack Obama’s election for the future of Black America. Like "
            },
            {
              "text": "Say Brother",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "text": "Basic Black",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " explored the past’s relevance for the present, with episodes reflecting on the role of "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-01pg65td",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Black Bostonian merchants"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " in the 19th century abolition movement, the history of the relationship between "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-676t239d",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "African Americans and Irish Americans"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " in Boston, and the experiences of African American soldiers during the "
            },
            {
              "type": "link",
              "url": "https://americanarchive.org/catalog/cpb-aacip-15-79h46j95",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Korean War"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": ". "
            },
            {
              "text": "Basic Black",
              "italic": true
            },
            {
              "text": " also celebrated Black culture through musical performances, poetry readings, and discussions of theater and film."
            }
          ]
        }
